{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17409758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17409758"},"attributes":{"position":2,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2772"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260860"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T04:55:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T05:01:27+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"new","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":3,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T05:00:17+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2772"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.02,0.54,0.21,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2772"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31411"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1423"},{"type":"tags","id":"1516"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29697"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 8-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of acute onset profuse vomiting and watery diarrhoea, which occurred after eating rice cereal for the first time. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. His parents report he attended his cousin\u0027s birthday party yesterday and had a small amount of cake, which he had previously eaten with no issues. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 180/min, blood pressure 70/40 mmHg, respiratory rate 60/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is hypotensive and floppy. He is managed with a 20 mL/kg bolus of intravenous 0.9% saline and makes a prompt recovery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rice allergy","Sepsis","Food protein-induced enterocolitis syndrome","Viral gastroenteritis","Coeliac disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFood protein-induced enterocolitis syndrome (FPIES)\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-IgE mediated reaction which occurs in infants, and is a highly reproducible food-protein induced gastrointestinal disease. Infants less than three months of age usually present after first exposure to cow\u0027s milk protein. Older infants often react to eggs, grains, rice and meats. Symptoms include profuse vomiting and diarrhoea within 1-3 hours of ingestion, associated with fluid-responsive hypotension and shock. Symptoms usually completely resolve after 72 hours of elimination of the allergen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to present so acutely, and would not cause hypotension. The symptoms also resolved promptly with fluid resuscitation, which would not be expected in coeliac disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral gastroenteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible differential, however it would not typically have such an acute onset of symptoms with fluid-responsive hypotension, which is a key feature of FPIES.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough rice may be the culprit for this FPIES reaction, a \u003Cstrong\u003Erice allergy\u003C/strong\u003E (IgE-mediated) would not cause such an acute episode with hypotension, and is also exceedingly rare. An IgE-mediated rice allergy could cause systemic symptoms such as a rash, urticaria and anaphylaxis, which can be managed with antihistamines or adrenaline in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E  \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely with this clinical picture, as the child was previously well and symptoms resolved rapidly with fluid resuscitation alone. Sepsis would be expected to cause persistent signs of shock requiring inotropic support and antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Food protein-induced enterocolitis syndrome (FPIES) is a non-IgE mediated reaction which occurs in infants, characterised by profuse vomiting, diarrhoea and shock within hours of ingesting the trigger food."],"references":["Kliegman, Robert., et al. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. Edition 20. Phialdelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2015","ASCIA Website: https://www.allergy.org.au/patients/food-other-adverse-reactions/food-protein-induced-enterocolitis-syndrome-fpies"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31411"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31411"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-05T17:50:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T15:02:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2772"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta